00:02:52.140 --> 00:02:55.700
Alright, now let’s head south to the Inca
civilization, which was older than the Aztecs

00:02:55.700 --> 00:02:59.260
and in some ways even more impressive. Founded
in the 13th century, the Inca empire ruled

00:02:59.260 --> 00:03:03.819
between 4 and 6 million people by the time
the Spanish showed up in 1532.

00:03:03.819 --> 00:03:06.389
Trade and a very effective administrative
structure held the empire together, which

00:03:06.389 --> 00:03:10.279
was even more impressive when you consider
all the roads and temples that were built

00:03:10.279 --> 00:03:15.319
atop mountains with nothing to haul things
up those mountains, except for llamas and people.

00:03:15.320 --> 00:03:18.919
The Inca had no written language but they
were able to keep records with knotted strings

00:03:18.919 --> 00:03:22.870
called quipus. And they were really good at
integrating conquered people into the empire,

00:03:22.870 --> 00:03:26.629
mandating that people learn the Incan language
and vitally, they ordered every male peasant

00:03:26.629 --> 00:03:31.380
under the Inca control to do unpaid work for the Inca
government for a specified period of time each year.

00:03:31.380 --> 00:03:34.859
This system, which the Inca called mit’a
allowed them to build all those roads and

00:03:34.859 --> 00:03:38.439
temples. The Spanish would later adopt this
system, and the hierarchical system with the

00:03:38.439 --> 00:03:42.319
emperor at the top, except they would make
it all, you know, much suckier. And, yes,

00:03:42.320 --> 00:03:44.079
that is a technical historian term.

00:03:44.079 --> 00:03:48.949
So, the Spanish arrived in Mexico in 1519,
and in Peru in 1532, benefiting in both cases

00:03:48.949 --> 00:03:53.139
from total chaos due to disease. And after
conquering the Inca and the Aztecs, they created

00:03:53.139 --> 00:03:57.339
an empire with two administrative divisions.
The Vice royalty of New Spain, founded in

00:03:57.339 --> 00:04:01.519
1521, and the Vice royality of Peru, founded
in 1542.

00:04:01.519 --> 00:04:05.699
In some ways, the Aztec and Inca empires were
perfect for Spanish conquest. Their administrative

00:04:05.699 --> 00:04:09.139
structures were similar, there was a similar
link between secular and religious power,

00:04:09.139 --> 00:04:12.799
albeit different religions. All of which made
it relatively easy for the Spanish crown to

00:04:12.799 --> 00:04:17.739
step into the void left by those two great empires
and send their own administrators to run the place.

00:04:17.739 --> 00:04:21.120
While most of the Spanish aristocrats who
came over ran large agricultural operations,

00:04:21.120 --> 00:04:25.419
you don’t see a lot of movies called, like,
Indiana Jones and the Search for A Nice Farm

00:04:25.419 --> 00:04:28.770
in the Countryside. The real glory for conquistadors
was gold.

00:04:28.770 --> 00:04:32.919
Initially they found some, both in the Caribbean
and in Mexico, but never enough to get, like,

00:04:32.919 --> 00:04:37.959
super-rich. Fortunately, or as I will argue,
unfortunately, they did find a mountain made of silver.

00:04:37.960 --> 00:04:42.060
So the Spanish adapted the mit'a, which the
Incas had used to build roads and public buildings,

00:04:42.069 --> 00:04:46.520
to mine and process that silver. So one seventh
of the adult male Indian population from each

00:04:46.520 --> 00:04:51.660
district was required to work in the silver mines
for a year, being paid only subsistence wages.

00:04:51.669 --> 00:04:55.289
Now, you might wonder why the Spanish didn’t
purchase African slaves to work in the mines.

00:04:55.289 --> 00:04:59.720
They did in Mexico, but in South America it
was cheaper to use indigenous labor.

00:04:59.720 --> 00:05:02.729
Purchasing slaves was inefficient because
one: They didn’t have experience working

00:05:02.729 --> 00:05:06.099
at high altitudes, and two: Mine work was
super deadly.

00:05:06.099 --> 00:05:10.150
Mercury, which can be used to refine silver
ore, was found at the mountain of Huancavelica.

00:05:10.150 --> 00:05:14.150
And mercury poisoning among miners was so
common that parents would often maim their

00:05:14.150 --> 00:05:18.669
children to keep them from having to work
the mines. You can see why I’m struggling

00:05:18.669 --> 00:05:21.259
to be festive! Let's go to the Thought Bubble.

00:05:21.259 --> 00:05:26.669
So Spanish mines in the Americas produced
over 150,000 tons of silver between the 16th

00:05:26.669 --> 00:05:31.659
and the 18th centuries, over 80% of the world’s
supply. Spain became the richest nation in

00:05:31.659 --> 00:05:34.669
Europe and Spanish silver pesos became the
de-facto currency.

00:05:34.669 --> 00:05:38.729
But the Spanish royal family does not appear
to have understood inflation, and the huge

00:05:38.729 --> 00:05:43.169
influx of silver caused skyrocketing inflation,
and since they never set tax rates to account

00:05:43.169 --> 00:05:47.979
for it, they collected the same amount of
money sixty years after the discovery of silver,

00:05:47.979 --> 00:05:52.349
but that money was worth a fraction of what
it once had been. And in general, it’s not

00:05:52.349 --> 00:05:55.629
clear that Spain benefited much from the discovery
of silver.

00:05:55.629 --> 00:05:59.889
Rich countries have a way of finding their
way into expensive and not totally necessary

00:05:59.889 --> 00:06:04.349
wars, and Spain was no exception. While empire
wasn’t the central cause of Spain’s many

00:06:04.349 --> 00:06:07.310
16th century wars, it sure did fund them.

00:06:07.310 --> 00:06:12.229
So in 1519, which was a heck of a year for
Spain, Charles V united the kingdoms of Spain

00:06:12.229 --> 00:06:17.189
and Austria by being named head of the Holy
Roman Empire, so called because it was not

00:06:17.189 --> 00:06:19.919
holy, not Roman, and not an empire.

00:06:19.919 --> 00:06:23.500
Charles had this dream of a unified central
Europe, which was constantly being thwarted

00:06:23.500 --> 00:06:28.280
by German nobles, who had a dream of a non-unified
central Europe, and eventually Charles V’s

00:06:28.280 --> 00:06:33.139
ambitions were shattered and he gave the Austrian
half of his kingdom to his son Ferdinand,

00:06:33.139 --> 00:06:36.629
and gave Spain with the American stuff to
Philip in 1556.

00:06:36.629 --> 00:06:40.710
Thanks, Thought Bubble. So, Philip II didn’t
only inherited all of Spain’s holdings in

00:06:40.710 --> 00:06:46.680
