00:07:19.120 --> 00:07:23.159
Anyway, American silver didn’t cause these
wars anymore than it wrote Hamlet, but the

00:07:23.159 --> 00:07:27.610
new wealth made both more possible. Knowing
that they had this enormous silver “war

00:07:27.610 --> 00:07:32.670
chest” at their disposal made them much more inclined
to build all those ships that got sunk in 1588.

00:07:32.670 --> 00:07:36.000
And soon enough even a mountain of silver
couldn't pay for all their warring, and the

00:07:36.009 --> 00:07:39.530
Spanish crown had to borrow money, which they
couldn’t pay back, so they defaulted on

00:07:39.530 --> 00:07:42.849
their debt several times in the 17th century.
Yay, silver!

00:07:42.849 --> 00:07:46.439
So, most of the silver mined in the Americas
went to Europe, but at least a third of it

00:07:46.439 --> 00:07:49.840
went to China. Either directly, on Spanish
galleons, or indirectly through through the

00:07:49.840 --> 00:07:51.370
purchase of Chinese goods.

00:07:51.370 --> 00:07:54.379
China had encountered inflation of its own
after printing the world’s first paper money

00:07:54.379 --> 00:07:58.099
in the 12th century, so they switched back
to coins. Initially, Chinese coins were made

00:07:58.099 --> 00:08:02.569
out of copper or bronze, but their economy
was so big — they were the leading producer

00:08:02.569 --> 00:08:06.419
of consumer goods until the 19th century — that
they ran out. So they went to silver.

00:08:06.419 --> 00:08:10.419
Now, China didn’t have a lot of silver itself,
but Japan did, so they traded manufactured

00:08:10.419 --> 00:08:14.110
goods for it, but soon even that wasn’t
enough. This was mostly because in the 16th

00:08:14.110 --> 00:08:19.779
century, China changed its tax structure.
Taxes, man, they’re at the center of human history.

00:08:19.779 --> 00:08:23.749
In the early part of the Ming Dynasty, Chinese
farmers paid their taxes in goods, mainly

00:08:23.749 --> 00:08:27.569
grain, and labor. But as more silver entered
the economy, the Ming government changed its

00:08:27.569 --> 00:08:30.849
policy and required taxes to be paid in silver.

00:08:30.849 --> 00:08:34.530
This meant that almost everyone in China had
to produce something that could be sold for

00:08:34.530 --> 00:08:38.820
silver, which usually meant silk. In fact, the Ming
government often required people to make silk.

00:08:38.820 --> 00:08:42.680
That glut of silk inevitably led to a price
drop, which hurt the Chinese economy but not

00:08:42.680 --> 00:08:47.000
nearly as much as it hurt the Spanish economy,
where almost every silk producer was put out

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:50.300
of business. So much for the idea that global
outsourcing is a new problem.

00:08:50.300 --> 00:08:53.660
You’d think all this silver would make the
